afe health care. Yet, the imperial system they encounter creates underlying conditions that greatly and disproportionately impact their ability to succeed and thrive, negatively impacting their reproductive health. Through clinical and community ethnography, Sarah A. Smith illuminates the way this system stratifies women’s reproduction at structural, social, and individual levels. Readers can visualize how U.S. imperialist policies of benign neglect control the body politic, change the social body, and render individual bodies vulnerable in the twenty-first century but also how people resist.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBirth controlxGovernment policyzGuam2DLC. 0aBirth controlxGovernment policyzGuam. 0aChuukese (Micronesian people)xSocial life and customs2DLC. 0aChuukese (Micronesian people)xSocial life and customs. 0aEthnologyzMicronesia (Federated States)2DLC. 0aEthnologyzMicronesia (Federated States). 0aImperialismxHealth aspects2DLC. 0aImperialismxHealth aspects. 0aMedical anthropology2DLC. 0aMedical anthropology. 0aWomen, ChuukesezGuamxSocial conditions2DLC. 0aWomen, ChuukesezGuamxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aguam, chuuk, us, united state, America, Oceania, colonialism, neo-colonialism, migration, immigration, emigration, health, health care, health policy, policy, public policy, reproductive care, women's health, free association, compacts of free association, pacific island, pacific islanders, chamorro, discrimination, inequality, micronesia, federated states of micronesia, chamoru.1 aManderson, Lenore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLET